# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
"""Places batch I — ICONIC MUST-VISITS ACROSS INDIA:
Hampi, Khajuraho, Konark, Mahabalipuram, Ellora, Ajanta, Pondicherry, Gujarat, Andaman."""
POSTS = []
def P(**k): POSTS.append(k)

P(slug="hampi", city="Hampi", region="Karnataka", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Hampi", query="Hampi Vijayanagara ruins",
  excerpt="A surreal UNESCO landscape of temple ruins and giant boulders — the vast, haunting capital of the mighty Vijayanagara Empire.",
  tags=["Hampi","UNESCO","ruins","history"],
  info=dict(timings="Sites sunrise–sunset; Vittala & Virupaksha have set hours", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign) for the main monuments",
            best="October–February; sunrise and sunset for the boulders", duration="2–3 days", reach="Northern Karnataka, near Hospet; ~6 hrs from Bengaluru"),
  body="""<p>Hampi is like nowhere else on earth — a vast, dreamlike landscape where the magnificent ruins of Vijayanagara, once one of the largest and richest cities in the world, are scattered across a boulder-strewn terrain of surreal beauty. At its 16th-century peak this was a metropolis of half a million people; today it's a UNESCO World Heritage Site of temples, palaces and bazaars slowly reclaimed by the rocks.</p>
<p>The Virupaksha Temple still hums with worship, the Vittala Temple complex holds the iconic stone chariot and 'musical' pillars, and sunrise or sunset over the giant granite boulders is unforgettable. It's a place to explore slowly, on foot, by bike or coracle across the river.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The stone chariot and musical pillars at the Vittala Temple.</li><li>The living Virupaksha Temple and its towering gopuram.</li><li>Sunset over the boulder landscape from Matanga or Hemakuta Hill.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The ruins are spread over a large area — hire a bike, scooter or guide. It gets very hot midday; explore at dawn and dusk. The 'Hippie Island' side across the river has a mellow traveller vibe (seasonal).</p>""")

P(slug="khajuraho-temples", city="Khajuraho", region="Madhya Pradesh", cat="Temple",
  name="Khajuraho Temples", query="Khajuraho temples",
  excerpt="A UNESCO group of 1,000-year-old temples covered in exquisite — and famously sensual — sculpture. A masterpiece of Indian art.",
  tags=["Khajuraho","UNESCO","temples","sculpture"],
  info=dict(timings="Western group sunrise–sunset; evening light & sound show", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign)",
            best="October–March; morning light", duration="Half day", reach="Madhya Pradesh; airport & rail connections"),
  body="""<p>Built by the Chandela dynasty between the 9th and 11th centuries, the temples of Khajuraho are among the finest achievements of Indian art and architecture — a UNESCO World Heritage Site famous worldwide for the extraordinary quality and sensuality of their sculpture. Every surface teems with gods, celestial dancers, animals and, most famously, intricately carved erotic figures.</p>
<p>Far from mere titillation, the carvings celebrate the full spectrum of life and are executed with breathtaking skill. The Western Group, dominated by the soaring Kandariya Mahadev temple, is the best preserved and most spectacular.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The Kandariya Mahadev, the largest and most ornate temple.</li><li>The exquisitely carved sculptural panels.</li><li>The evening sound-and-light show.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The Western Group is the essential visit and the only ticketed one. A guide greatly enriches the sculpture's meaning. The annual dance festival (usually Feb) is a beautiful time to visit.</p>""")

P(slug="konark-sun-temple", city="Konark", region="Odisha", cat="Temple",
  name="Konark Sun Temple", query="Konark Sun Temple",
  excerpt="A colossal 13th-century temple built as the sun god's chariot, with 24 carved stone wheels — a UNESCO wonder of Odisha.",
  tags=["Konark","UNESCO","temple","chariot"],
  info=dict(timings="Sunrise – sunset (daily)", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign)",
            best="Morning; the Dec dance festival", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="Coastal Odisha, ~35 km from Puri / ~65 km from Bhubaneswar"),
  body="""<p>The Konark Sun Temple is one of the most awe-inspiring monuments in India — a 13th-century masterpiece conceived as the gigantic chariot of Surya, the sun god, drawn by seven stone horses and riding on 24 intricately carved wheels. A UNESCO World Heritage Site, its scale and artistry are staggering.</p>
<p>The famous stone wheels double as functioning sundials, and the entire temple, covered in exquisite carvings of daily life, deities and dancers, is a triumph of Kalinga architecture. Though the main tower has collapsed over the centuries, what remains is monumental.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The 24 elaborately carved chariot wheels (and their sundial function).</li><li>The stone horses and the grand entrance.</li><li>The detailed friezes covering the structure.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>A guide helps decode the symbolism and the sundials. It pairs naturally with Puri (Jagannath Temple) and the beach. The December Konark Dance Festival is spectacular.</p>""")

P(slug="mahabalipuram", city="Mahabalipuram", region="Tamil Nadu", cat="Landmark",
  name="Mahabalipuram (Mamallapuram)", query="Mahabalipuram Shore Temple",
  excerpt="A UNESCO ensemble of 7th-century rock-cut temples and giant carvings by the sea — the crowning glory of Pallava art.",
  tags=["Tamil Nadu","UNESCO","rock-cut","coast"],
  info=dict(timings="Shore Temple sunrise–sunset; other monuments open-access", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign) for the Shore Temple",
            best="Morning or late afternoon", duration="Half day", reach="Coastal Tamil Nadu, ~55 km south of Chennai"),
  body="""<p>On the Coromandel coast south of Chennai, Mahabalipuram is an open-air museum of 7th- and 8th-century Pallava art — a UNESCO World Heritage Site of rock-cut temples, monolithic shrines and colossal bas-reliefs carved straight from the living granite. It's one of South India's essential stops.</p>
<p>The elegant Shore Temple stands sentinel over the sea; the five Pancha Rathas are each carved from a single boulder; and 'Arjuna's Penance' is one of the largest rock reliefs in the world. Add the gravity-defying Krishna's Butter Ball and a laid-back beach-town vibe, and it's a delight.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The seafront Shore Temple.</li><li>The monolithic Pancha Rathas (Five Chariots).</li><li>The vast 'Arjuna's Penance' rock relief and Krishna's Butter Ball.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Only the Shore Temple and Pancha Rathas are ticketed; much is free to wander. It's an easy day trip from Chennai, or a relaxed overnight with the beach and stone-carving workshops.</p>""")

P(slug="ellora-caves", city="Ellora", region="Maharashtra", cat="Landmark",
  name="Ellora Caves", query="Ellora Caves Kailasa temple",
  excerpt="34 rock-cut monasteries and temples of three faiths — crowned by Kailasa, the largest monolithic structure ever carved. A UNESCO site.",
  tags=["Ellora","UNESCO","caves","rock-cut"],
  info=dict(timings="Sunrise – sunset (closed Tuesdays)", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign)",
            best="Morning; October–March", duration="Half day", reach="~30 km from Aurangabad (Chhatrapati Sambhajinagar), Maharashtra"),
  body="""<p>The Ellora Caves are one of the greatest rock-cut wonders of the world — 34 monasteries and temples carved into a basalt cliff over five centuries, and remarkable for representing three religions (Buddhism, Hinduism and Jainism) side by side in harmony. It's a UNESCO World Heritage Site of staggering ambition.</p>
<p>Its crowning achievement is the Kailasa Temple (Cave 16): the largest single monolithic rock excavation on earth, carved top-down from a single piece of rock to resemble a freestanding temple, complete with courtyards, sculptures and elephants. Standing before it is genuinely humbling.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The colossal monolithic Kailasa Temple.</li><li>The Buddhist prayer halls and Jain shrines.</li><li>The intricate sculptural panels throughout.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Closed on Tuesdays (Ajanta is closed Mondays — plan the pair carefully). Aurangabad is the base for both. A guide brings the astonishing engineering to life.</p>""")

P(slug="ajanta-caves", city="Ajanta", region="Maharashtra", cat="Landmark",
  name="Ajanta Caves", query="Ajanta Caves paintings",
  excerpt="Ancient Buddhist cave temples hidden in a horseshoe gorge — home to some of the finest surviving paintings of the ancient world.",
  tags=["Ajanta","UNESCO","caves","paintings"],
  info=dict(timings="Sunrise – sunset (closed Mondays)", entry="Approx ₹40 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign)",
            best="Morning; October–March", duration="Half to full day", reach="~100 km from Aurangabad, Maharashtra"),
  body="""<p>Carved into a dramatic horseshoe-shaped cliff above a river gorge, the Ajanta Caves are a UNESCO World Heritage Site of 30 Buddhist rock-cut monasteries and prayer halls dating back over 2,000 years. Rediscovered by a British hunting party in 1819 after centuries of abandonment, they are a window into the ancient world.</p>
<p>Their glory is the painting: the caves preserve some of the finest and best-preserved murals of ancient India, depicting the life of the Buddha and the Jataka tales in glowing, sophisticated detail. Together with their serene sculptures, they are a treasure of world art.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The exquisite ancient murals (especially in Caves 1, 2, 16 and 17).</li><li>The great chaitya (prayer hall) caves and their stupas.</li><li>The panoramic viewpoint across the gorge.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Closed on Mondays. Photography without flash is allowed but the paintings are dim (lit carefully to preserve them). Aurangabad is the base; combine with Ellora on separate days.</p>""")

P(slug="pondicherry-french-quarter", city="Puducherry", region="Puducherry", cat="Landmark",
  name="Pondicherry (French Quarter)", query="Pondicherry French Quarter White Town",
  excerpt="A sun-washed former French colony of mustard-yellow villas, bougainvillea and seaside cafés — India with a Gallic soul.",
  tags=["Pondicherry","French","coast","charming"],
  info=dict(timings="Wander any time; the Promenade is best at dawn & evening", entry="Free",
            best="November–February", duration="1–2 days", reach="Coastal Puducherry, ~3 hrs south of Chennai"),
  body="""<p>Pondicherry (Puducherry) is India with an unexpected French accent. Its charming 'White Town' quarter is a grid of quiet, tree-lined streets edged with mustard-yellow colonial villas, French street signs, chic boutiques and cafés serving croissants and filter coffee alike — a genuinely unique atmosphere on India's east coast.</p>
<p>Life centres on the seafront Promenade (Rock Beach), lovely at dawn and in the evening when it's closed to traffic. Add the serene Sri Aurobindo Ashram, the experimental township of Auroville nearby, and a laid-back beachy pace, and it's a favourite weekend escape.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Wandering the French Quarter's photogenic streets.</li><li>The seaside Promenade at sunrise or evening.</li><li>The Sri Aurobindo Ashram and nearby Auroville.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The French Quarter is small and best explored on foot or by bicycle. Weekends draw crowds from Chennai — weekdays are calmer. It's also known (unusually for the region) for its bars and relaxed nightlife.</p>""")

P(slug="rann-of-kutch", city="Kutch", region="Gujarat", cat="Desert",
  name="Rann of Kutch", query="Rann of Kutch white desert",
  excerpt="A vast, blinding-white salt desert that stretches to the horizon — magical under a full moon, and home to the great Rann Utsav.",
  tags=["Gujarat","salt desert","Rann Utsav","landscape"],
  info=dict(timings="Best at sunset & full moon; Rann Utsav runs winter", entry="Permit required for the border area; Utsav has packages",
            best="November–February (Rann Utsav); full-moon nights", duration="1–2 days", reach="Kutch district, western Gujarat; base at Bhuj/Dhordo"),
  body="""<p>The Great Rann of Kutch is one of India's most otherworldly landscapes — a seemingly endless expanse of cracked white salt flats that merge with the sky at the horizon. In the monsoon it floods; in winter it dries into a dazzling white desert that glows almost luminous under a full moon.</p>
<p>Each winter the region hosts the Rann Utsav, a vibrant festival of tented accommodation, Kutchi handicrafts, folk music and dance that has made this remote frontier accessible and unforgettable. The surrounding Kutch region is also famed for its exquisite embroidery and artisan villages.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The white salt desert at sunset and under a full moon.</li><li>The Rann Utsav festival and tented city.</li><li>The Kutchi handicraft and embroidery villages.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The white desert is near the sensitive Pakistan border — a permit is required (easily arranged). It's best in winter; the full-moon nights are the most magical. Nights get cold — pack layers.</p>""")

P(slug="statue-of-unity-gujarat", city="Kevadia", region="Gujarat", cat="Landmark",
  name="Statue of Unity", query="Statue of Unity Gujarat",
  excerpt="The tallest statue in the world — a 182-metre tribute to Sardar Patel, rising beside the Narmada dam amid a vast new tourist complex.",
  tags=["Gujarat","statue","landmark","modern"],
  info=dict(timings="~8 AM – 6 PM (closed Mondays); viewing gallery timed", entry="Ticketed (viewing gallery costs more; book online)",
            best="Morning; the laser/light show in the evening", duration="Half day", reach="Kevadia (Ekta Nagar), Gujarat; ~90 km from Vadodara"),
  body="""<p>At 182 metres, the Statue of Unity is the tallest statue in the world — nearly twice the height of the Statue of Liberty. It depicts Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel, the statesman who unified India's princely states after independence, and stands dramatically beside the Narmada River and Sardar Sarovar Dam.</p>
<p>Beyond the sheer scale, the site has grown into a sprawling tourist complex with a viewing gallery near the statue's chest, a museum, gardens, a jungle safari, boating and an evening laser-and-light show — a modern mega-attraction set against the Satpura hills.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The viewing gallery high inside the statue.</li><li>The evening laser light-and-sound show.</li><li>The Valley of Flowers gardens and river views.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Closed on Mondays. Book the viewing-gallery ticket online in advance — it sells out. There's plenty around it to fill a half or full day.</p>""")

P(slug="radhanagar-beach-andaman", city="Havelock Island", region="Andaman & Nicobar", cat="Beach",
  name="Radhanagar Beach", query="Radhanagar Beach Havelock Andaman",
  excerpt="Regularly rated among Asia's best beaches — a pristine curve of powder-white sand and turquoise sea on Havelock Island.",
  tags=["Andaman","beach","island","turquoise"],
  info=dict(timings="Open all day; lifeguards until evening", entry="Free",
            best="October–May (avoid monsoon)", duration="A day (or an island stay)", reach="Havelock (Swaraj Dweep) Island; ferry from Port Blair"),
  body="""<p>Far out in the Bay of Bengal, Radhanagar Beach on Havelock Island is regularly ranked among the finest beaches in Asia — and it earns it. A long, gentle arc of soft white sand backed by dense forest, fronting impossibly clear turquoise water, it's the tropical-paradise beach that most people don't realise India has.</p>
<p>The Andaman Islands as a whole are a world apart — coral reefs, world-class scuba diving and snorkelling, and a slow, blissful island pace. Radhanagar is the jewel, especially at sunset when the sky and sea blaze with colour.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Sunset over the turquoise water.</li><li>Swimming and snorkelling in the clear, calm sea.</li><li>Scuba diving around Havelock's reefs.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Reaching Havelock means a flight to Port Blair then a ferry — plan a few days to make it worthwhile. Avoid the monsoon (roughly May–Sept). Carry cash; connectivity and ATMs are limited on the islands.</p>""")
